			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1900">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Jamie Berger&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href="/article/374">Peep Show</a>&rdquo; [February 2005] could have been written just for me. My curiosity about peep shows goes back many, many years, to an impotent boyfriend who admitted to being a peep-show addict. He didn&rsquo;t tell me what went on, though. I never dreamed that perhaps he got to touch the women and to ejaculate. I thought the men just looked!</p>

<p>That boyfriend and I used to watch porno movies in my bedroom, but he still couldn&rsquo;t perform. I wish that I could have talked with him then about his addiction and asked if he was able to ejaculate at the peep show. When I see him now, the question is on my lips, but then I wonder what difference it would make: he&rsquo;s sixty-nine, and I&rsquo;m seventy.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Name Withheld<br></p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1901">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>In his emotionally honest and thoughtful essay &ldquo;Peep Show,&rdquo; Jamie Berger talks about wanting eye contact from strippers: in a sense, needing forgiveness and intimacy from them at the same time that he is engaging in this objectifying and shameful (to him) behavior. If I were a sex worker, I might think he&rsquo;s asking for a lot more than he&rsquo;s paying for. And is the forgiveness Berger seeks real if he&rsquo;s paying for it? I think he knows it isn&rsquo;t, which is why he needed to be under&shy;stood by the radical-dyke audience at his reading.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;ve been a member of the sex-positive dyke community for more than a decade, and I love the liberation of it. The most important question for me is: What about all the women who, like Berger, were instilled by their parents with shame about their sexuality? He is one of a tiny number of men who&rsquo;ve been hurt by the feminist movement. Meanwhile, girls everywhere grow up repressed and vulnerable to sexual abuse. Where&rsquo;s their sex-positive haven? Where&rsquo;s the forgiving eye contact for them? Not in a peep show, that&rsquo;s for sure.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Suzy Subways<br>Philadelphia, Pennsylvania</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1902">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Although I appreciate the honesty with which Jamie Berger told his tale, I was offended by the implicit messages: that moms who teach their children feminist values run the risk of raising sex addicts; that abject objectification of women is <span class="smallcaps">OK</span>; and that you can avoid responsibility for your problems by blaming your parents. I hope someone will suggest a good twelve-step group for Berger, who is so obviously powerless over certain urges. And I hope <em>The Sun</em>&rsquo;s editors will reconsider the next time they are tempted to publish something this cheap and incendiary in hopes of boosting circulation.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jennifer Miles<br>Longmont, Colorado</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="1903">
								<p><a href="/contributors/jamie-berger"><strong>Jamie Berger</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>Suzy Subways brings up a point that I wish I had addressed more fully in the essay: I was indeed looking for much more than I was paying for, and the dancers had no reason whatsoever to give it to me. I would like to add that, as much as I was &ldquo;hurt by the feminist movement,&rdquo; I was also helped and educated by it in innumerable ways.</p>

<p>Regarding Miles&rsquo;s assertions: It seems that when a writer doesn&rsquo;t take sides on a polarized issue, readers will often insist on forcing the writer into one camp or the other. The assumption that I find &ldquo;the abject objectification of women&rdquo; <span class="smallcaps">OK</span> does not logically follow from what I wrote, even if one presumes to read between the lines. The messages that Miles felt were &ldquo;implicit&rdquo; &mdash; especially regarding feminist moms creating &ldquo;sex addicts&rdquo; &mdash; are contrary to the aim of &ldquo;Peep Show.&rdquo; I give my parents much more credit than blame for who I have become as an adult. I&rsquo;m disappointed if the piece read otherwise to Miles. Happily, my parents didn&rsquo;t read it that way.</p>
	</div>


					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

